# Dockerfile for the Modal-hosted vLLM container that serves
# Qwen 3.5 9B at FP8 e4m3 (lovedheart/Qwen3.5-9B-FP8) on H100:1.
# History: B200/H200 bf16 27B pre-2026-05-21 cutover → H100 Qwen3.5-9B
# bf16 → H100 Qwen3.6-27B-FP8 (iter-09..iter-14) → H100 Qwen3.5-9B-FP8
# (iter-15, 2026-05-24, machine-consciousness-conference demo). The
# bf16 / FP8 / 27B / 9B history is captured in the auto-memory entries
# iter14_snapshot_load_working + iter14_cold_start_hardening + this
# header. Gemma 4 31B paused 2026-05-20 — see app.py module docstring.
#
# Built once and pushed by `modal deploy -m qr_sampler.connectors.modal.app`.
#
# Base image notes
# ----------------
# The base tag MUST satisfy all of the following:
#   * Hopper / H200 CUDA support (vLLM v0.17.0 ships matching CUDA wheels).
#   * V1 engine (`AdapterLogitsProcessor`) -- ours plugs in via the
#     `vllm.logits_processors` entry point.
#   * Loads Qwen/Qwen3.5-9B (qwen3_5 GDN). The architecture entry only
#     exists in transformers `main`, which the layer below installs over
#     the base.
#
# Build (Modal does this automatically from `Image.from_dockerfile`):
#   modal deploy -m qr_sampler.connectors.modal.app

# vLLM v0.17.0 is the V1 engine release whose bundled transformers still
# pins <5. The Qwen3.5-9B architecture we need to load (qwen3_5 GDN /
# Qwen3_5ForConditionalGeneration) requires transformers>=5 (the
# registration lives on `main`, not in any tagged release yet). We
# override transformers below with --no-deps so vLLM's other pinned
# siblings (tokenizers, safetensors, ...) keep their vLLM-validated
# versions. Recipe mirrors C:/Code/createmp-evalsuite/modal_app.py
# lines 46-67 which has already proven this combination loads Qwen3.5-9B
# on Modal. The 9B has the same model_type=qwen3_5 + vision encoder as
# the 27B; if vLLM's V1 ``profile_run`` MM dummy probe regresses at this
# version, see the ``vllm.hf.config_probe`` event in modal logs -- it
# records the HF ``architectures`` + ``has_vision_config`` fields used
# to triage.
#
# Why we reverted v0.21.0 -> v0.17.0 (2026-05-20)
# -----------------------------------------------
# The 2026-05-20 bump to v0.21.0 was attempted to pull in Gemma4 support
# but produced two consecutive cold-start failures: (1) Gemma4 hit
# ``max_tokens_per_mm_item (2496) > max_num_batched_tokens (2048)``
# because vLLM's MM auto-config silently dropped our 4096 override; (2)
# Qwen3.5-9B hit a ``StopIteration`` inside transformers ``Qwen3VLProcessor.
# get_text_with_replacements`` from V1's unconditional MM dummy probe.
# Neither knob (``limit_mm_per_prompt`` / ``max_num_batched_tokens``)
# suppressed the probe. Reverting to v0.17.0 mirrors the
# createmp-evalsuite-validated recipe; Gemma is paused (see app.py
# module docstring) until vLLM ships a release with both Gemma4 GDN
# support AND a workable text-only MM-probe knob.
# iter-14 (2026-05-23): TODO — pin by digest, not tag. Tags on the
# vllm/vllm-openai DockerHub repo are MUTABLE (vLLM has retagged
# v0.17.0 in the past for security backports). To pin: run
#   docker pull vllm/vllm-openai:v0.17.0
#   docker inspect --format='{{index .RepoDigests 0}}' vllm/vllm-openai:v0.17.0
# then replace the tag-based FROM below with
#   FROM vllm/vllm-openai@sha256:<digest>
# Until that is done, this image's reproducibility is at the mercy of
# upstream maintainers re-tagging v0.17.0. predeploy.ps1 surfaces a
# warning when the FROM line does not start with `vllm/vllm-openai@`.
ARG VLLM_BASE_TAG=v0.17.0
FROM vllm/vllm-openai:${VLLM_BASE_TAG}

# iter-09 (2026-05-21): VLLM_LOGGING_LEVEL = INFO now that iter-08 closed
# the EngineCore 500 cascade by fixing --host 0.0.0.0 (see
# qr-llm-chat/LEARNINGS.md iter-08). Flip to DEBUG for one cold-start
# whenever investigating a future engine-internal issue; DEBUG is a
# 10-100x log-volume blow-up over INFO at production traffic.
#
# Phase 3 iter-05 / iter-10: TORCH_NCCL_ENABLE_MONITORING=0 stops the
# NCCL HeartbeatMonitor from emitting dump-on-timeout payloads after a
# Modal GPU snapshot/restore (the watchdog probes a TCPStore socket
# whose FD didn't survive the snapshot). iter-10 adds two further
# silencers to suppress the residual broken-pipe warnings the env var
# alone could not stop:
#   * TORCH_NCCL_HEARTBEAT_TIMEOUT_SEC=86400 — pushes the heartbeat
#     check interval out to 24h so the runLoop effectively never fires
#     in a container's lifetime; combined with the monitoring flag
#     above this neutralises the broken-pipe spam at its source.
#   * TORCH_CPP_LOG_LEVEL=ERROR — the broken-pipe messages we still
#     saw on iter-09 (``[W521 ProcessGroupNCCL.cpp:1802] ... Broken
#     pipe``) are PyTorch C++ WARNINGs. Bumping the C++ log level to
#     ERROR suppresses them without affecting Python-level vLLM logs.
# Single-GPU tensor_parallel=1 means NCCL has no collectives to watch
# anyway, so the monitor + heartbeat were pure noise post-snapshot.
ENV PYTHONDONTWRITEBYTECODE=1 \
    PYTHONUNBUFFERED=1 \
    VLLM_LOGGING_LEVEL=INFO \
    VLLM_SERVER_DEV_MODE=1 \
    HF_HUB_ENABLE_HF_TRANSFER=1 \
    TORCH_NCCL_ENABLE_MONITORING=0 \
    TORCH_NCCL_HEARTBEAT_TIMEOUT_SEC=86400 \
    TORCH_CPP_LOG_LEVEL=ERROR \
    TORCHINDUCTOR_COMPILE_THREADS=1
# TORCHINDUCTOR_COMPILE_THREADS=1 is the Modal-documented fix for
# torch.compile + memory snapshot conflicts (see
# https://modal.com/docs/guide/memory-snapshots — "In certain cases,
# running the Torch Compiler can cause Memory Snapshot creation to
# fail"). Without this, the inductor's multi-threaded compile produces
# CUDA driver state that NVIDIA's cuda-checkpoint --get-state cannot
# enumerate within its 180 s timeout during snapshot RESTORE — symptom
# is ``CudaCheckpointException: Failed to restore 1 processes: Get
# state command timed out`` (see modal/_runtime/gpu_memory_snapshot.py
# in the SDK). Single-threaded compile makes the resulting CUDA state
# enumerable.

# The vllm/vllm-openai base ships only `python3.12` + `pip` on PATH (pip's
# shebang hardcodes /usr/local/bin/python3.12). Modal's image-attach step
# probes a bare `python` to determine the interpreter version when
# `add_python` is unset; without this symlink it errors with
# "We were unable to determine the version of Python installed in the
# Image". We deliberately do NOT set `add_python` because it would create a
# parallel interpreter that does not see vllm/torch/CUDA from the base
# (see src/qr_sampler/connectors/modal/app.py:vllm_image comment block for
# the full reasoning).
RUN ln -sf "$(command -v python3.12 || command -v python3 || command -v python)" \
        /usr/local/bin/python \
    && python --version

WORKDIR /opt/qr-sampler

# Copy only pyproject.toml first to leverage Docker layer caching.
COPY pyproject.toml ./
COPY src/ ./src/

# Install qr-sampler (with gRPC support) + the runtime libraries the Modal
# entrypoint needs. huggingface_hub is required for the one-shot weights
# download. fastapi/httpx/grpcio are runtime deps for the dispatcher and
# the QRNG gRPC client.
RUN pip install --no-cache-dir . \
    && pip install --no-cache-dir \
        "huggingface_hub>=0.30" \
        "fastapi>=0.110" \
        "httpx>=0.27" \
        "grpcio>=1.62"

# --- apt deps for transformers@main + cloudflared sidecar ------------------
#
# Single apt layer to keep image size down. `git` is required by the
# transformers @ main install below — pip's `git+https` schema invokes
# `git clone` inside the container, and the vllm/vllm-openai base does
# not ship git. `curl` + `ca-certificates` are needed by the cloudflared
# .deb download in the next block. Mirrors
# createmp-evalsuite/modal_app.py line 47 (.apt_install("git")) which is
# the empirically-proven baseline for the transformers@main layer.
RUN apt-get update \
    && apt-get install -y --no-install-recommends \
        git \
        curl \
        ca-certificates \
    && rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*

# --- transformers main override (qwen3_5 GDN architecture) -----------------
#
# vLLM 0.17.0 pins transformers<5 in its wheel, but the qwen3_5 GDN
# architecture (Qwen3.5-9B / Qwen3.6-27B) only lands in transformers main
# (v5.x) -- it is not in any tagged release at the time of writing. We
# install transformers@<pinned-commit> with --no-deps so vLLM's other
# pinned siblings (tokenizers, safetensors, ...) keep their vLLM-validated
# versions. Mirrors createmp-evalsuite/modal_app.py lines 64-67 (the
# empirically proven recipe for the 9B; both Qwen3_5 sizes share the same
# model_type).
#
# transformers pin: tagged release v5.5.4 (was commit 52b82b2 from main,
# replaced 2026-05-20 after iteration 1's StopIteration crash).
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Why v5.5.4 over a main commit:
#   (1) Iteration 1 with commit 52b82b2 crashed inside
#       ``Qwen3VLProcessor`` at engine init time:
#         ValueError: Failed to apply Qwen3VLProcessor on
#         data={'text': '<|vision_start|><|image_pad|><|vision_end|>'}
#       The dummy generator emitted text-only data (no paired images)
#       to a processor that requires both. A known transformers
#       regression on certain main commits; v5.5.x is past it.
#   (2) Reproducible builds. ``@main`` is a moving target; tagged
#       releases never drift.
#   (3) v5.5.4 is the version currently installed in the local dev
#       venv; using it in the container too keeps deploy and local
#       smoke-test behaviour aligned.
#   (4) Per the vLLM Qwen3.5-9B recipe (recipes.vllm.ai/Qwen/
#       Qwen3.5-9B), the model "works out of the box" with default
#       MM enabled. With v5.5.4 transformers, that recipe applies to
#       our deploy too.
#
# mistral_common upgrade (>= 1.10):
#   ``ReasoningEffort`` lands in mistral_common's
#   ``protocol.instruct.request`` around 1.6+; pinning >=1.10 gives a
#   comfortable margin without risking incompatibility with vLLM
#   0.17.0's other consumers. transformers v5.5.4 lazily imports
#   ``tokenization_mistral_common`` from inside
#   ``processing_utils.get_possibly_dynamic_module`` while resolving
#   the ``Qwen3VLProcessor`` class registry -- a code path we cannot
#   avoid from a vLLM-side knob.
#
# huggingface_hub upgrade (>= 0.30):
#   transformers v5.5.4 requires it.
RUN pip install --no-cache-dir --no-deps \
        "transformers==5.5.4" \
    && pip install --no-cache-dir --upgrade \
        "huggingface_hub>=0.30.0" \
        "mistral_common>=1.10"

# --- cloudflared sidecar for QRNG reachability -----------------------------
#
# The QRNG gRPC service (qbert-grpc.cipherstone.co) is published behind a
# Cloudflare Zero Trust Access TCP application. Modal workers reach it via
# a per-container `cloudflared access tcp` sidecar that opens a loopback
# listener at 127.0.0.1:50051 and forwards every byte through Cloudflare's
# edge to the tunnel origin. Auth is a Service Token (CF_ACCESS_CLIENT_ID +
# CF_ACCESS_CLIENT_SECRET) provisioned in the cipherstone Cloudflare team.
#
# Sidecar lifecycle is owned by `qr_sampler.connectors.modal.cloudflared_sidecar`;
# it is started in `@modal.enter(snap=False)` (post-restore) so no live socket
# is captured in the snapshot.
#
# `cloudflared` is a single static binary — no daemon, no kernel modules, no
# NET_ADMIN capability. Installing from the official .deb (rather than `apt
# install cloudflared`, which is not in Debian's default repos) keeps us on a
# pinned-by-URL recent build.
#
# iter-14 (2026-05-23): kept `/releases/latest/download/` because pinning to
# a specific cloudflared version requires looking up the release tag +
# its SHA256 from web (unavailable in offline build env). HOWEVER we now
# CAPTURE THE VERSION + SHA in the build log so each image build records
# exactly which cloudflared bytes ended up in it — a snapshot identity
# drift between deploys is then trivially detectable via the
# `cloudflared.version` + `cloudflared.sha256` lines in the build log,
# even without enforcing the pin in advance.
#
# Follow-up: once the deploy host has been on the network we can pin the
# release tag and switch to `sha256sum -c` enforcement (the version
# capture below makes the SHA we need visible). At that point the
# `/releases/latest/download/` URL becomes
# `/releases/download/<version>/cloudflared-linux-amd64.deb`.
RUN set -eux \
    && curl -fsSL \
        https://github.com/cloudflare/cloudflared/releases/latest/download/cloudflared-linux-amd64.deb \
        -o /tmp/cloudflared.deb \
    && echo "cloudflared.sha256 $(sha256sum /tmp/cloudflared.deb | cut -d' ' -f1)" \
    && dpkg -i /tmp/cloudflared.deb \
    && echo "cloudflared.version $(cloudflared --version 2>&1 | head -1)" \
    && rm /tmp/cloudflared.deb

# Default qr-sampler configuration. Overridden by the Modal Secret at runtime.
# The defaults below match the QRNG service (cf. artifacts/qrng.proto):
#   - method path: /qrng.QuantumRNG/GetRandomBytes (unary only — qrng.proto
#     does not define a streaming RPC).
#   - api-key header: literal "api-key" (lowercase), per the QRNG team's
#     contract in artifacts/README.md.
#   - sample count: 12800 = comfortably under the 13000-byte-per-request
#     limit of the production API key.
#   - fallback: `system` (os.urandom) so a transient cloudflared outage
#     degrades to CSPRNG entropy rather than aborting inference. The
#     FallbackEntropySource layer emits a structured DEGRADED warning on
#     every fallback so operators see the degradation in `modal app logs`.
ENV QR_ENTROPY_SOURCE_TYPE=quantum_grpc \
    QR_PREINIT_ENTROPY_SOURCES=quantum_grpc,system \
    QR_FALLBACK_MODE=system \
    QR_SAMPLE_COUNT=12800 \
    QR_GRPC_SERVER_ADDRESS=127.0.0.1:50051 \
    QR_GRPC_MODE=unary \
    QR_GRPC_METHOD_PATH=/qrng.QuantumRNG/GetRandomBytes \
    QR_GRPC_STREAM_METHOD_PATH= \
    QR_GRPC_API_KEY_HEADER=api-key \
    QR_PRESET=creative_sampling

# 2026-05-21: VLLM_ENABLE_V1_MULTIPROCESSING=0 was previously set here to
# avoid signal-propagation issues with EngineCore subprocess during
# Modal's snapshot lifecycle. But empirically this caused every chat
# completion to fail with "EngineCore encountered an issue. See stack
# trace (above) for the root cause." — vLLM 0.17.0's V1 engine still
# spawns EngineCore_DP0 even with this flag set, and the resulting
# main-process scheduler ends up in a broken sync path that aborts
# every generation request with no traceback in modal logs. The
# original signal-propagation issue was already fixed by other Phase H
# changes (post_restore sequencing in vllm_serve.py). Default value is
# fine; restore the env var only if "Engine core proc died unexpectedly"
# resurfaces during cold-start.

# Reset ENTRYPOINT set by vllm/vllm-openai base image so Modal's @modal.enter
# method controls process start (not `vllm serve`).
ENTRYPOINT []
CMD ["python", "-m", "deployments.modal.vllm_serve"]
